text.text:
This place is pretty small. The table we sat at was a high top and pretty uncomfortable. There wasn’t enough room on the table for our food.

The bartender was so nice though. After she saw I didn’t drink my drink she asked if I wanted to swap and I did! It didn’t like it at all. I got the color and co. Which looked gorgeous. But didn’t taste sweet and fruity like the description said. Maybe it was the egg whites I didn’t like but I thought the drink tasted like plastic. She made me a paper plane with no complaints and that was good.

The happy hour deals are pretty good, for $20 you can get two share plates or an entree and a share plate. The food was just okay though. The chicken sandwhich was pretty spicy and was covered in coleslaw or something. I liked the big pickle with it though. The chicken wings were too spicy too and kind of dry. The salad I had should have been bigger.

If you are in the area I recommend to try another place for food.

text.text:
As someone who grew up savoring the flavors of pav bhaji in India, revisiting Honest Restaurant was like taking a trip down memory lane. Located on the busy bleaker street of the city, this humble eatery holds a special place in my heart, thanks to its authentic and flavorsome rendition of pav bhaji.From the moment I stepped inside, the aroma of freshly cooked spices filled the air, instantly transporting me back to the bustling streets of Mumbai and Gujarat.

The ambiance is simple yet inviting, with cheerful staff ready to greet you with warm smiles.Now, onto the star of the show – the pav bhaji. Honest Restaurant's rendition of this classic street food dish is nothing short of exceptional. The bhaji, a rich medley of mashed vegetables cooked to perfection, is infused with just the right amount of spice, making each bite a burst of flavor. Paired with soft, buttery pav bread, it's a match made in culinary heaven.

Honest Restaurant is a must-visit destination. So, if you find yourself craving a taste of authentic pav bhaji, look no further than Honest Restaurant – where every bite is a trip back home.

editorialSummary.text: Elaborate French classics are served in this chic, contemporary space with banquette & bar seating.

text.text:
Beautiful spot in NYC with good service.
The food was good, I tried 6 different dishes including dessert, food was cooked properly, a sign of a skilled chef, I enjoyed all of the dishes but in terms of how good the dishes were, they were good but not good enough or creative enough to be memorable or to make me come back again, French cuisine is complex and I'm judging this restaurant by those standards.
Dessert wasn't bad but also wasn't satisfying. I tried two dishes from the menu and non of them made me go for a second or third spoon.
The most disappointing part is the wine menu, I tried all the whites and all the reds by the glass, and non of the listed wines do justice to Burgundy or Bordeaux or French wine in general, and also they do not pair well with the food served, yes they mentioned that they are working on their wine menu but for a French cuisine they can do much better than this, I also tried one of their cocktails and mentioned that I don't want it to be overly sweet, they adjusted the ingredients and added so much ginger that I only tasted ginger in the drink.
Friendly staff and I hope that they look into these minor details, such a beautiful spot needs more attention and creativity
I don't know how this restaurant was before the pandemic, I'm only reviewing it by my recent experience.
